=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">In the post-cable universe=E2=80=94where r=
atings declines are
inevitable, streaming dreams are quixotic, and multiplatform appeal is the =
coin of the realm=E2=80=94ESPN appears to be pinning its hopes on an <em>en=
ormous </em>investment in live sports rights, an <em>even</em> <em>more eno=
rmous </em>investment in new platforms (Flagship, Venu, etcetera), and the =
anointment of a core group of talent known in Bristol as <em>the needle-mov=
ers</em>. There=E2=80=99s <strong>Pat McAfee</strong>, whom ESPN is paying =
$17 million per year to license his show. There=E2=80=99s <em>First
Take</em> host <strong>Stephen A. Smith</strong>, who is drying the ink on =
a deal that will pay him at least $20 million per year. Then there=E2=80=99=
s <em>Get Up</em>=E2=80=99s <strong>Mike Greenberg</strong> and <em>SportsC=
enter</em>=E2=80=99s <strong>Scott Van Pelt</strong>, two other talents for=
 which ESPN execs would gladly back up a Brink=E2=80=99s truck, though both=
 Greeny and SVP make far less than Stephen A.=E2=80=99s asking price and wh=
at McAfee=E2=80=99s show costs.</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;"=
>=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">McAfee=E2=80=99s arrang=
ement is unique, of course, because it isn=E2=80=99t exclusive. The sleevel=
ess former punter built his audience on YouTube before signing a lucrative =
licensing deal with ESPN. Stephen A. is a homegrown talent, but his pending=
 deal also includes some nonexclusive opportunities=E2=80=94if, say, he wan=
ts to start his own lifestyle-themed radio show or pop-culture play. (Steph=
en A. has appeared as a guest on Fox News.) Greenberg and Van Pelt represen=
t a slightly
different tranche of talent: more old school, with radio chops, pre- and po=
stgame bona fides, etcetera=E2=80=94the <strong>Posada </strong>and <strong=
>Pettitte </strong>of this core-four ensemble, you might say.</p><p style=
=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;">Greeny an=
d SVP joined me on recent episodes of the <em>Varsity</em> podcast, where I=
 spoke with each about McAfee and Stephen A.=E2=80=99s deals and where they=
 fit into this new ecosystem. It=E2=80=99s clear they believe those deals h=
ave
set a precedent for ESPN=E2=80=99s top on-air talent, and one that should a=
pply to them. I found their responses illuminating, so I am including them =
here, lightly edited, as always, for clarity.</p></div>
